{
  "doc_id": "17121",
  "text": "Brain-derived neurotrophic factor (BDNF) is a neurotrophin that promotes cell survival and death, neuronal maturation, and has a prominent role in long-term synaptic plasticity and psychiatric pathophysiology [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] Yoshii and ConstantinePaton, 2010) . The strong correlation between stress or antidepressant treatment and down-or upregulation, respectively, of BDNF in limbic brain regions has led to the 'neurotrophin hypothesis of depression' [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . In agreement with this hypothesis, studies in animal models and humans have shown that physical exercise that reduces depressive symptoms is accompanied by an increase in brain levels of BDNF [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] .",
